<span id="viii.v.iv.v-p1"></span> <span class="c4"><span
id="viii.v.iv.v-p1.1"></span>Canon V.</span>

<span id="viii.v.iv.v-p2"></span><span class="sc"><span
id="viii.v.iv.v-p2.1"></span>If</span> any one shall teach that the
house of God and the assemblies held therein are to be despised, let him
be anathema.

<span id="viii.v.iv.v-p3"></span><span class="c4"><span
id="viii.v.iv.v-p3.1"></span>Notes.</span>

<span id="viii.v.iv.v-p4"></span><span class="sc"><span
id="viii.v.iv.v-p4.1"></span>Ancient Epitome of Canon V.</span>

<span id="viii.v.iv.v-p5"></span>Whoso styles the house of God
contemptible, let him be anathema.

<span id="viii.v.iv.v-p6"></span>This canon is found in the *Corpus
Juris Canonici*, Gratian’s *Decretum*, Pars I., Dist. xxx., c. x.  The
commentators find nothing to say upon the canon, and in fact the
despising of the worship of God’s true church is and always has been so
common a sin, that it hardly calls for comment; no one will forget that
the Prophet Malachi complains how in his days there were those who
deemed “the table of the Lord contemptible” and said of his worship
“what a weariness is it.”  ([Mal. 1:7](../../../bib/kjv/mal001.htm#007.md),
[13](../../../bib/kjv/mal001.htm#013.md)<span
id="viii.v.iv.v-p6.1"></span>.)

